<br>
I thought the director did a good job with building the tension and he had some really good shots.  It's always nice to see directors doing less with more, one single green leg can be scary.<br>
<br>
If you liked the idea in the movie that there are no coincidences, that everything is a part of God's plan, I would highly recommend John Irving's <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> A Prayer for Owen Meany</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> which dealt with the same themes far better.  I hope I didn't make the book sound too preachy...it's at times irreverent and profane (and wonderfully funny), but at the end, well, I find it hard to explain since few books have ever affected me that way. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uerynlor.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Erynlor</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 105<br> <font color=#E9D756>(8/6/02 1:51:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=10278.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Signs</span><hr size=1> Ghie,<br>
<br>
I guess what you are dissatisfied with are the unacceptable attempts at subplots.  Given your formula, the following one sentence plots can be made:<br>
<br>
citizen kane: money/power cant buy you happiness.<br>
<br>
godfather: i thought my father was stupid for doing whatever it took to protect his family and make a living; i was wrong.<br>
<br>
matrix/wizzard of oz: wake up dorothy, this isnt kansas.<br>
<br>
The SOMEWHAT smallish subplots of: <br>
Phoenix's redemption at always swinging away; to thine ownself be true. <br>
a boy's realization that his father is someone to be admired; parents are people too.<br>
Phoenix's plea for Gibson to return to being the 'rock' that he so desperately needed; where have all the heros gone.<br>
this is also played out by the townpeople who are reluctant to give up on Gibson as a religious leader...at a time when they need to believe the most.<br>
<br>
The subplots are there.  Small in scope maybe, but that is also an artistic statement.   One thing that has bothered me since Pulp Fiction is the silly notion of introducing disjointed subplots, and the weirder the better, is 'artsy' and true cinema.   <br>
<br>
Pulp Fiction pulled it off...but none of the clones have.  Just because something is different and unexpected does not make it good.   In fact, the mark of a really good artist, be they actor, director or writer, is to take a familiar subject, and present it in a way that captivates its audience even when they know what's coming.<br>
<br>
A Rebel X-Wing fighter coming in at the last second to save the hero would not have made Saving Private Ryan nor Glitter better movies.  It would have been bizzare and unexpected...but totally stupid.<br>
<br>
erynlor <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#E9D756>- </font><a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/bemarr>Erollisi Marr, The Queen of Love</a><font color=#E9D756> - </font><a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrgeneral>General</a> <font color=#E9D756> - </font> <br>
